## Hand-Written Contract

The `MainService` interface must be hand-written, never inferred. `type MainService = ReturnType<typeof create>` exposes every plugin internal as public API and causes TS7056 on `.d.ts` emit because the combined plugin chain exceeds serialization limits.

Write the interface explicitly (`extends Service`), and let `create()` return it without casting so TypeScript verifies assignability:

```ts
// types/main-service/main-service.ts
export interface MainService extends Service {
  readonly archetypes: { readonly Track: ReadonlyArchetype<Track>; /* ... */ };
  readonly observe:      { /* every resource/component observable by hand */ };
  readonly transactions: { /* every transaction signature by hand */ };
  readonly actions:      { /* every action by hand */ };
  readonly computed:     { /* every computed by hand */ };
  readonly services:     { /* every nested service by hand */ };
}

// types/main-service/create/create.ts
export function create(overrides: Partial<CoreServices> = {}): MainService {
  const services = CoreServices.initialize(overrides);
  // DO NOT cast as MainService — we want TS to verify assignability.
  return Database.create(plugin, { services });
}
```

The interface exposes only `observe.*`, `computed.*`, `transactions.*`, `actions.*`, `services.*`. No `get`, `read`, `select`, or archetype write access on the public surface. Adding a new capability is a conscious decision to expose it to UI.

## Readonly Archetypes

Use `ReadonlyArchetype<T>` for archetypes on the public surface, and return `Readonly<T>` from entity observations. This prevents UI from mutating entity data through the archetype handle:

```ts
readonly archetypes: {
  readonly Track:     ReadonlyArchetype<Track>;
  readonly TrackItem: ReadonlyArchetype<TrackItem>;
};

entity(id: Entity, archetype: ReadonlyArchetype<Track>):     Observe<Readonly<Track>     | null>;
entity(id: Entity, archetype: ReadonlyArchetype<TrackItem>): Observe<Readonly<TrackItem> | null>;
```

