# Main Service Interface

## Hand-Written Contract

The `MainService` interface must be hand-written, never inferred. `type MainService = ReturnType<typeof create>` exposes every plugin
internal as public API and causes TS7056 on `.d.ts` emit because the combined plugin chain exceeds serialization limits.

Write the interface explicitly (`extends Service`), and let `create()` return it without casting so TypeScript verifies assignability:

```ts
// types/main-service/main-service.ts
export interface MainService extends Service {
  readonly archetypes: { readonly Track: ReadonlyArchetype<Track> /* ... */ };
  readonly observe: {
    /* every resource/component observable by hand */
  };
  readonly transactions: {
    /* every transaction signature by hand */
  };
  readonly actions: {
    /* every action by hand */
  };
  readonly computed: {
    /* every computed by hand */
  };
  readonly services: {
    /* every nested service by hand */
  };
}

// types/main-service/create/create.ts
export function create(overrides: Partial<CoreServices> = {}): MainService {
  const services = CoreServices.initialize(overrides);
  // DO NOT cast as MainService — we want TS to verify assignability.
  return Database.create(plugin, { services });
}
```

The interface exposes only `observe.*`, `computed.*`, `transactions.*`, `actions.*`, `services.*`. No `get`, `read`, `select`, or archetype
write access on the public surface. Adding a new capability is a conscious decision to expose it to UI.

## Plugin additions require a matching interface entry

A new transaction in `plugins/transactions/<name>.ts` or a new computed in `plugins/computed/<name>.ts` is invisible to UI until its
signature is added to `main-service.ts`. The plugin file carries `/** @internal */`; the interface entry is the public surface.

```ts
// types/main-service/main-service.ts
readonly computed: {
  readonly effectivePixelsPerFlick: Observe<number>;
  readonly trackDuration:           (trackId: Entity) => Observe<TimelineDuration>;
  readonly myNewComputed:           Observe<MyShape>;          // added with the plugin
};

readonly transactions: {
  readonly multiUpdateTrackItems: (args: MultiUpdateTrackItemsArgs) => void;
  readonly setRotationDegrees:    (args: SetRotationArgs) => void;   // added with the plugin
};
```

Exactly one line per capability. If an addition is intentionally plugin-private, leave it off the interface — but do not call it from any
binding either. The rule is: "in the interface" = "callable from UI"; "not in the interface" = "plugin-internal, unreachable from UI."

Pre-merge check: every new or renamed file under `plugins/{transactions,computed}/` in the diff has a matching added line in
`main-service.ts`. A diff that adds a plugin file without an interface entry is either incomplete (the UI call site will never type-check)
or the capability is plugin-private (in which case remove the speculative plugin file).

## Readonly Archetypes

Use `ReadonlyArchetype<T>` for archetypes on the public surface, and return `Readonly<T>` from entity observations. This prevents UI from
mutating entity data through the archetype handle:

```ts
readonly archetypes: {
  readonly Track:     ReadonlyArchetype<Track>;
  readonly TrackItem: ReadonlyArchetype<TrackItem>;
};

entity(id: Entity, archetype: ReadonlyArchetype<Track>):     Observe<Readonly<Track>     | null>;
entity(id: Entity, archetype: ReadonlyArchetype<TrackItem>): Observe<Readonly<TrackItem> | null>;
```

